\b 3. Lessons Learned\b0\par
The main lesson from this project was that parser extensions are easier to debug when grammar changes are made in small steps. Adding one language feature at a time made it much easier to tell whether a new shift/reduce conflict or recovery problem came from the most recent change.\par
\par
Another lesson was that operator precedence is clearer and safer when it is encoded structurally in the grammar. Building separate nonterminals for each precedence level made the intended associativity explicit and avoided relying on precedence directives that were prohibited by the assignment.\par
\par
I also learned that error recovery needs to be designed around realistic synchronization points. Generic recovery rules can cause cascaded errors, while targeted recovery rules tied to semicolons, case clauses, and statement boundaries allow the parser to resume in a more stable state.\par
\par
If this project were extended further, the next improvement would be to automate the test suite so each supplied input file is run by a single script and compared against expected outcomes. Another useful improvement would be adding semantic analysis on top of the parser so duplicate declarations, undeclared identifiers, and type mismatches could be reported in the same listing format.\par
